%I A393525 #39 Apr 05 2026 11:12:37
%S A393525 3,5,11,23,47,2879,1065601,1985902081,21981381119,13357981992959,
%T A393525 568000797112319,1136001594224639,3105111850422067201,
%U A393525 567357957277949460481,1134715914555898920961
%N A393525 Consider the following transformation of prime numbers: If b(n) == 1 (mod 4) then b(n+1) = (b(n) + 1)/2. If b(n) == 3 (mod 4) then b(n+1) = (b(n) - 1)/2. Continue this transformation until a nonprime is reached. a(n) is the least prime number such that exactly n primes appear in the chain of numbers created by this transformation.
%C A393525 Sequence made at the suggestion of _Thomas Ordowski_ and with the assistance of _Amiram Eldar_.
%C A393525 a(10) > 3 * 10^11.
%C A393525 Is this sequence strictly increasing?
%e A393525 a(5) = 47 because under the described transformation 47 -> 23 -> 11 -> 5 -> 3 -> 1. This longest full chain contains 5 prime numbers and 47 is the least prime with this property.
%o A393525 (Python)
%o A393525 from sympy import isprime, nextprime
%o A393525 terms, x = {}, 3
%o A393525 while len(terms) < 7: # program is slow for a(8) and beyond
%o A393525     y = x
%o A393525     steps = 0
%o A393525     while y > 0 and isprime(y):
%o A393525         steps += 1
%o A393525         if y % 4 == 1:
%o A393525             y = (y+1)//2
%o A393525         elif y % 4 == 3:
%o A393525             y = (y-1)//2
%o A393525     if steps not in terms:
%o A393525         terms[steps] = x
%o A393525     x = nextprime(x)
%o A393525 for z in terms:
%o A393525     print(terms[z], end=", ")
%Y A393525 Cf. A110092, A110093, A110095.
%K A393525 nonn,more
%O A393525 1,1
%A A393525 _David Consiglio, Jr._, Mar 18 2026
